    <h1>Valuation - Tiered Direct Capitalization & NOI</h1>
    <h2>How the NOI Statement is used in the Tiered Direct Capitalization method</h2>
    <p>
      The idea underpinning the Tiered method of Direct Capitalization is that
      portions of a property are so different in value that each component or
      “Tier” should be valued separately. The Tiered method still uses the
      Standard Direct Capitalization method, but instead of one valuation
      calculation, it is the sum of the value of each Tier.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Tiered method requires that separate NOI Statements for each Tier are
      built which combined add up to the NOI Statement for the property as a
      whole.
    </p>
    <hr class="mt-4 mb-4 border-gray-300">
    <h2>Example</h2>
    <p>
      Let’s say we are using the NOI Statement below which has been broken into
      two tiers–one for a low risk tenant which has a Capitalization Rate of 7%
      and a second, higher risk tenant which has a Capitalization Rate of 10%.
    </p>
    <p>
      How would the property be valued using the Tiered Capitalization method,
      this time using the Trailing 12-month NOI?
    </p>
