    <p>
      The first step is splitting the total property into two Tiers–a tier for
      the lower risk tenant and a tier for the higher risk tenant.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <div class="rounded-md shadow-sm border border-gray-300 overflow-auto max-w-fit">
        <table class="table-auto border-collapse font-medium">
          <tbody>
            <tr class="bg-white">
              <th class="border-b py-3 font-semibold text-left px-8 whitespace-nowrap">Net Operating Income</th>
              <td class="border-b py-3 text-right px-8 font-semibold border-l">$2,025</td>
              <td class="border-b py-3 text-right px-8 font-semibold">$2,175</td>
              <td class="border-b py-3 text-right px-8 font-semibold">$4,200</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50">
              <th class="border-b py-3 font-medium text-left px-8 pl-12 whitespace-nowrap text-gray-700">Capitalization Rate</th>
              <td class="border-b py-3 text-right px-8 border-l">7.0%</td>
              <td class="border-b py-3 text-right px-8">10.0%</td>
              <td class="border-b py-3 text-right px-8">8.29%<sup>**</sup></td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white">
              <th class="py-3 font-semibold text-left px-8 whitespace-nowrap">Valuation</th>
              <td class="py-3 text-right px-8 font-semibold border-l">$28,929</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-right px-8 font-semibold">$21,750</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-right px-8 font-semibold">$50,679</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <small class="text-left">
        <sup>**</sup> The combined Capitalization Rate for the property is
        calculated by dividing the total NOI by the total Valuation. It is equal
        to the weighted average (by NOI) of the Capitalization Rates of the
        tiers.
      </small>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The value of the property is $50,679, using the Tiered Capitalization
      method is calculated by adding together the values of each of the two
      tiers.
    </p>
    <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1 list-disc pl-8">
      <li class="text-gray-800 text-base font-medium">
        The value of Tier 1 ($28,929) is calculated by dividing the actual NOI
        for the next year ($2,025) by the Capitalization Rate (7%).
      </li>
      <li class="text-gray-800 text-base font-medium">
        The value of Tier 1 ($21,750) is calculated by dividing the actual NOI
        for the next year ($2,175) by the Capitalization Rate (10%).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Notice how the Capitalization Rate plays a huge role in determining the
      value of each Tier. While Tier 2 has a higher NOI, the higher
      Capitalization Rate causes the valuation to be much lower than the Tier 1
      valuation.
    </p>
